U.S. Legislators called on Japan to openits financial markets to more foreign participation and boostits efforts to head off growing U.S. Protectionism, a ForeignMinistry spokesman said.    "We have come to seek the opening of Japan's financial andbanking markets," Jake Garn, ranking Republican on the SenateBanking Committee, told Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone.    "Japan's financial and banking market is very large andincreasingly sophisticated, but there is not yet truereciprocity between Japan and the United States in this market,"the ministry official quoted Garn as saying.    Nakasone replied that some problems exist over providingmore seats on the Tokyo Stock Exchange for foreign firms, oneof the main steps urged by the U.S. Delegation.    "But I promise to make Tokyo's markets as open as those ofNew York," he told Garn and three other legislators.    In separate talks with Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa,the U.S. Group also urged Japan to give U.S. Financialinstitutions a bigger role in the underwriting of long-termJapanese government bonds, a Finance Ministry spokesman said. REUTER&#3;